

# Day 7: Domain & DNS Reconnaissance

## Introduction

Day 7 of my 30 Days of OSINT (Open Source Intelligence) Challenge.

Today, I explored Domain & DNS Reconnaissance, one of the core techniques in Open Source Intelligence used to gather publicly
available information about websites, domains, and their underlying infrastructure.
Every website on the internet operates under a domain name, and behind every domain is a Domain Name System (DNS) 
that translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses. By analyzing DNS records and domain information, 
investigators can understand how a website is configured, identify its publicly exposed services, and build a clearer picture of an organization's online infrastructure.
Domain & DNS Reconnaissance is widely used in cybersecurity, penetration testing, bug bounty programs, threat intelligence, digital forensics,
and incident response. The objective is to collect publicly available information ethically and use it to improve security awareness or support legitimate investigations.


